`foreach` + `await` will run `Process`es sequentially.
```
    public async Task ProcessInputAsync(T input)
    {
        foreach (var processor in m_processors)
        {
            await processor.Process(input));
        }
    }
```

Btw. `Process`, should be called `ProcessAsync`

The method [`Task.ContinueWith`][1] does not understand async delegates, like [`Task.Run`][2] do, so when you return a `Task` it considers this as a normal return value and wraps it in another `Task`. So you end up receiving a `Task&lt;Task&gt;` instead of what you expected to get. The problem would be obvious if the `AsyncProcessor.Process` was returning a generic `Task&lt;T&gt;`. In this case you would get a compile error because of the illegal casting from `Task&lt;Task&lt;T&gt;&gt;` to `Task&lt;T&gt;`. In your case you cast from `Task&lt;Task&gt;` to `Task`, which is legal, since [`Task&lt;TResult&gt;`][3] derives from `Task`.

Solving the problem is easy. You just need to unwrap the `Task&lt;Task&gt;` to a simple `Task`, and there is a built-in method [`Unwrap`][4] that does exactly that.

There is another problem that you need to solve though. Currently your code suppresses all exceptions that may occur on each individual `AsyncProcessor.Process`, which I don&#39;t think it was intended. So you must decide which strategy to follow in this case. Are you going to propagate the first exception immediately, or you prefer to cache them all and propagate them at the end bundled in an [`AggregateException`][5], like the [`Task.WhenAll`][6] does? The example bellow implements the first strategy.

    public class CompositeAsyncProcessor&lt;T&gt;
    {
        //...
        public Task Process(T input)
        {
            Task current = Task.CompletedTask;
            foreach (AsyncProcessor&lt;T&gt; processor in m_processors)
            {
                current = current.ContinueWith(antecessor =&gt;
                {
                    if (antecessor.IsFaulted)
                        return Task.FromException&lt;T&gt;(antecessor.Exception.InnerException);
                    return processor.Process(input);
                },
                    CancellationToken.None,
                    TaskContinuationOptions.ExecuteSynchronously,
                    TaskScheduler.Default
                ).Unwrap();
            }
            return current;
        }
    }

I have used an overload of `ContinueWith` that allows configuring all the options, because the defaults are not ideal. The default [`TaskContinuationOptions`][7] is `None`. Configuring it to `ExecuteSynchronously` you minimize the thread switches, since each continuation will run in the same thread that completed the previous one.

The default task scheduler is [`TaskScheduler.Current`][8]. By specifying `TaskScheduler.Default` you make it explicit that you want the continuations to run in thread-pool threads (for some exceptional cases that won&#39;t be able to run synchronously). The `TaskScheduler.Current` is context specific, and if it ever surprises you it won&#39;t be in a good way.

As you see there are a lot of gotchas with the old-school `ContinueWith` approach. Using the modern `await` in a loop is a lot easier to implement, and a lot more difficult to get it wrong.

  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.task.continuewith
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.task.run
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.task-1?view=netframework-4.8
  [4]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.taskextensions.unwrap
  [5]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.aggregateexception
  [6]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.task.whenall
  [7]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.taskcontinuationoptions
  [8]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.taskscheduler.current

